00:00:06.720 --> 00:00:11.650
CINE, the Council on International Non-Theatrical events has awarded this film

00:00:11.650 --> 00:00:15.670
a Golden Eagle in token of its
excellence and has selected it to

00:00:15.670 --> 00:00:19.990
represent the United States of America
in international motion picture events abroad.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:33.000
Farewell, ETAOIN SHRDLU, Mixtrack take one

00:01:35.210 --> 00:01:40.350
We are fast approaching press time for
the first edition of tomorrow morning's

00:01:40.350 --> 00:01:46.440
paper. This printer has just finished
makeup of a page. In the next 56 minutes,

00:01:46.440 --> 00:01:51.360
all pages must be finished and recorded
to meet the Edition deadline of 9:00 PM.

00:01:51.360 --> 00:02:00.480
But tonight's deadline is special...
this New York Times mirror image inlet

00:02:00.480 --> 00:02:12.000
of tomorrow's date line reads backwards
as Sunday July 2nd 1978. It marks the

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:18.209
last day of an age-old method of
printing in this composing room. What you

00:02:18.209 --> 00:02:23.280
are now witnessing will exist after
tonight only as a film historic record,

00:02:23.280 --> 00:02:30.900
for the century of the linotype machine
is nearing its end. Using 535 degree

00:02:30.900 --> 00:02:36.900
molten lead it sets solid lines of type
called hot type cast in newspaper

00:02:36.900 --> 00:02:43.500
column width. Now cooled, a printer's
hands prepare the lines for insertion

00:02:43.500 --> 00:02:52.200
into a column of the page. Headlines are
still set by hand with type stored in

00:02:52.200 --> 00:02:58.470
traditional California cases and in time-worn
Ludlow cabinets, by morning relics

00:02:58.470 --> 00:03:04.680
of the past. Letter by letter the printer
forms the words in his composing stick,

00:03:04.680 --> 00:03:09.299
in the same way that Gutenberg, the
first printer of the western world, did

00:03:09.299 --> 00:03:14.760
more than five centuries ago.
Brass moulds of letters are assembled in

00:03:14.760 --> 00:03:24.560
a different composing stick also for
headlines. Inside this Ludlow machine,

00:03:24.560 --> 00:03:30.210
which was invented a quarter of a
century after the linotype, they will be

00:03:30.210 --> 00:03:39.990
cast from liquid lead to form a solid
slug of type. By tomorrow, this Ludlow too

00:03:39.990 --> 00:03:45.540
will be a museum piece.
These steel tables for page make up are

00:03:45.540 --> 00:03:50.160
called printer stones. They have been
gradually abandoned over the past months.

00:03:50.160 --> 00:03:56.780
A radical changeover has taken place,
for a new era of computerized, electronic,

00:03:56.780 --> 00:04:03.150
automated, and cold type photo technology
has begun. It started in the brightly lit

00:04:03.150 --> 00:04:09.570
area beyond these two dark hopes of
discarded linotype machines. Now lined up

